{"cursor":"10921","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Paul Berg |image =Paul Berg in 1980.jpg |image_size\n=150px |caption = Paul Berg in 1980 |birth_date = |birth_place = Brooklyn, New\nYork |death_date = |death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality =\nU.S. |ethnicity = |field = Biochemistry |work_institutions = Stanford\nUniversity |alma_mater = Case Western Reserve University Pennsylvania\nState University |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for =\nrecombinant DNA |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences =\n|influenced = |prizes = Nobel Prize in Chemistry (1980) |religion = |footnotes =\n|signature = |spouse=Mildred Levy (m. 1947; 1 child) [http://books.google.ca/books?id=uPRB-\nOED1bcC&pg=PA55&dq=Mildred+Levy++Berg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bk4YUcL2E8PWygHEuICYAQ&ved=-\n0CCMQ6AEwAA] }} 'Paul Berg' (born June 30, 1926) is an American biochemist\nand professor emeritus at Stanford University. He was the recipient of the Nobel\nPrize in Chemistry in 1980, along with Walter Gilbert and Frederick Sanger. The\naward recognized their contributions to basic research involving nucleic acids.\nBerg received his undergraduate education at Penn State University, where he\nmajored in biochemistry. He received his Ph.D. in biochemistry from Case Western\nReserve University in 1952. Berg worked as a professor at Washington University\nSchool of Medicine and Stanford University School of Medicine, in addition to\nserving as the director of the Beckman Center for Molecular and Genetic\nMedicine. In addition to the Nobel Prize, Berg was presented with the National\nMedal of Science in 1983 and the National Library of Medicine Medal in 1986.\n","linknr":917,"url":"Paul_Berg","recorded":1376415958,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Paul_Berg&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Paul_Berg&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecomm